lines: 外務省＿総合外交対策局長
外務省＿総合外交対策局長
外務省＿総合外交対策局長
texts: Once Graham Kingly finished explaining why the operation had failed, the stage was set for the others in attendance to speak up.
The Minister of Defense bore the brunt of the criticism.
Were you not supposed to settle this peacefully?! How did things escalate this far?!
The restoration works may have familiarized the citizens with military activity, but this is ridiculous!
Do you think media silence comes cheap?!
And after all that, you still failed!
I heard you even overrode traffic lights and civilian vehicles. When did I ever allow cracking in public?!
Those were not the actions of our army operators. Do not misattribute it.
It doesn't matter who did it. It's still a stick for the opposition to beat us with.
And we're already under fire from the public as it is.
Would it make sense to blame the Ministry of Foreign Affairs for having given into their demands so thoughtlessly?
Demands that bypass proper diplomatic routes ought to be rejected immediately. What would you say to that?
Do you honestly think Japan has the power to refuse? The last 50 years have mutilated this country.
The divide between the government and its people is so vast we'd need more than a few decades to fix it.
Even after we formed the JUSDF, it was simply dismantled and incorporated into the US Army.
That's exactly the sort of thing that's left this country weaker than ever.
We are not here today to discuss such things.
外務省＿総合外交対策局長
B-besides, this was all approved by the prime minister, anyway...

texts.name: 外務省＿総合外交対策局長

texts: I'll thank you not to drag him into this. We must act as if this were something we decided on our own.
外務省＿総合外交対策局長
We never demanded the mobilization of the army...

texts.name: 外務省＿総合外交対策局長

texts: What were we supposed to do, exactly?
We were to secure a girl we knew nothing about, while refraining from investigating her altogether. It was simply absurd.
Such things are beyond our control. We are not at fault!
And even if we did use the army, what alternative did we have?
They were the only ones we could mobilize quickly and discreetly. I'm certain I informed you of this.
Any other units would have necessitated half a year's worth of paperwork.
Even so, using live ammunition was a bridge too far.
The army does things its own way.
外務省＿総合外交対策局長
We've received a complaint from the Vatican regarding the failure of the operation...

texts.name: 外務省＿総合外交対策局長

texts: So? Do they want to strangle the one responsible?
The failure rests on my shoulders.
I am prepared to accept any punishment I deserve. I ask only that my subordinates be spared.
No one present had the official authority to impose punishment on Graham. This meeting itself was unofficial, and would remain off-record.
The awkward silence continued until the MLIT representative broke it.
That's a good point. Capturing the girl would have been simple using GAIA's predictions, wouldn't it?
Or perhaps you did use them, and failed anyway?
Is GAIA some hunk of scrap incapable of finding a single girl? I very much doubt it!
Indeed. GAIA exists to bring an end to this era in which the Vatican has power over us.
Speaking of which, why isn't Soga here? I'm quite certain we called him.
That was when Ewan Okuda, who was standing next to Graham, opened his mouth for the first time since entering the room.
GAIA has been inactive for the last two days due to the scheduled maintenance of the quantum computer unit.
The head researcher is currently in charge of this operation and thus cannot leave GAIA's side.
There is also the possibility that forcing GAIA to operate while under maintenance would have caused further issues.
Issues that would have taken even more time to address.
The head researcher refused to gamble your GAIA on this mystery girl.
However, he did rendezvous with the unit, as ordered, while the operation was still ongoing.
If you wish to complain regardless, please share your complaints with me, and I will relay them to him.
We did as the Vatican told us. That alone is enough. The results do not matter.
This time, the silence was broken by the Minister of Defense—the only one seated in a position directly facing Graham and Ewan.
With those words, everyone in the room was freed from the troublesome matter, and the mood in the room became lighter.
The Minister of Defense glared at Graham and Ewan.
Resume your original mission. You will not be punished for this.
Dispose of the documents you were provided, as well as all data you gathered during the operation. And tell Soga to do the same.
